Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry all produce.

Drain and rinse @chickpeas{13.4%ounce}; pat very dry with #paper towels{}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @sour cream{4%tablespoon}, 2 TBSP @feta cheese{1/2%cup} (you'll use the rest later), and @olive oil{1%tablespoon}. Add water 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> 4 SERVINGS: Use 4 TBSP feta.

Toss chickpeas and @cauliflower florets{10%ounce} on a #baking sheet{} with a large drizzle of @olive oil{2%teaspoon}, @Turkish spice blend{1%tablespoon}, and a couple big pinches of @salt{}.

Roast on top rack until chickpeas are crispy and cauliflower is tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

> TIP: It's natural for chickpeas to pop a bit while roasting!

While chickpeas and cauliflower roast, in a #small pot{}, combine @Israeli couscous{3/4%cup}, 3/4 cup @water{3/4%cup}, @veggie stock concentrate{1}, and a big pinch of @salt{}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce heat to low. Cook until couscous is tender, ~{6-8%minutes}. Keep covered off heat.

> 4 SERVINGS: Use 1 1/2 cups water.

Pick @cilantro{1/4%ounce} leaves from stems; roughly tear leaves. Stir half the cilantro, remaining feta, and @butter{1%tablespoon} into cooked couscous. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Divide couscous between shallow #bowls{}. Top with chickpeas and cauliflower. Drizzle with feta sauce. Garnish with remaining cilantro and serve.

> 4 SERVINGS: Use 2 TBSP butter.